{"attack":true,"case":"The target's first forbidden case is self-refuting under std-crit-design clauses (1) and (2). It proposes holding global (p=0.5, phi=0.6, psi=0.5, k=5) fixed while varying the per-question flag-correlation structure, then asserts that harness-vs-SC deltas differing by <10 pp would falsify the claim that per-question structure matters. But the target's own mechanism proves the opposite: phi and psi are deterministic functions of the per-question flag rates r_w(q) and r_c(q). If r_w(q)>r_c(q) on SC-wrong questions (helpful alignment), the harness fixes wrong majorities; if r_c(q)>r_w(q) on SC-right questions (harmful alignment), it breaks correct ones. These are exactly the two structures the forbidden case juxtaposes. The mechanism therefore entails a large delta between them — the <10 pp outcome the case forbids is one the proposal's own math rules out. A forbidden case that cannot occur is not a measurable outcome of running the experiment, violating clause (2)'s requirement that forbidden cases be concrete measurable results the harness could actually produce. More sharply: the target supplies no forbidden case for the intermediate regime where per-question correlation is mixed (some questions helpful, some harmful, net effect ambiguous). The claim asserts strict improvement arises 'only when' r_w>r_c on wrong-majority questions, yet the proposal never pre-registers a threshold on the aggregate correlation (e.g., mean(r_w-r_c) over SC-wrong questions) below which strict advantage must vanish. Without such a threshold the central claim is unfalsifiable: any null result can be attributed to insufficient per-question alignment rather than refuting the mechanism. This violates clause (1)'s requirement for a measurable regime condition and clause (2)'s requirement that forbidden cases would genuinely refute the proposal had they obtained.","counterexample":null}